Please use a common typeface, such as Arial (sans-serif) or Times New Roman (serif).
The font size should be 12 points, and the line spacing should be set to one and a half.

The exposé should demonstrate that you:
- Have formulated a precise research question.
- Possess a general idea of how to address the question (basic methodology).
- Can explain the relevance of your work.
- Are familiar with the most pertinent literature in your research area.
- Recognize common challenges in your research domain.
- Have realistic expectations regarding the time needed for research and writing.

Writing the exposé marks the first critical step in your thesis journey, laying the foundation for your project.
The proposal serves as a guide for both you and your supervisor, ensuring a successful outcome within the expected timeframe.

== Introduction (1/2 page)

The introduction should provide you and future readers of your thesis with a broader understanding of the context and background of your research topic.
This encompasses the problem area, connections to other fields, and the significance of your topic from both practical and theoretical perspectives.

It is crucial to outline why your work is engaging and how it fits into current research within the field.
The introduction will basically become the first chapter of your thesis, so it's essential to establish a problem and capture the reader's interest early on.
You can achieve this by starting with a hook, a statement that piques the reader's curiosity and motivates them to engage with your proposal.
The hook should be intriguing enough to encourage readers to delve further into your work.
Whenever possible, introduce your case with examples, concrete events, or thought-provoking statements.

Next, provide a concise overview of your thesis's relationship with related work (a more detailed discussion will follow in the subsequent chapter).
Briefly describe how this problem or issue has been addressed in the past, and by whom.
Identify gaps in existing research that your thesis aims to fill.
Convey the core aspects of your approach, focusing on what the reader needs to understand why your research is relevant to the questions and issues you've outlined.
Provide a brief, clear description of your research question, field, and methods.


== Related Work (1/2 page)

In this section, introduce the most influential works (approximately 3 or 4) related to your research.
These works may share a similar scope or have inspired your research.

Most topics are not confined to a single body of literature.
Typically, they encompass different research traditions or perspectives.
Your task is to integrate these perspectives or provide new viewpoints on topics that have not been researched extensively.
For example, you may critique a research problem that has been primarily addressed theoretically, neglecting practical implications or empirical evidence.

In this chapter, express your understanding of the current academic debate and how your work fits into it.
While you cannot cover all aspects, aim to provide an excellent overview of key literature.
Acknowledge those who originally proposed the ideas you are building upon and those who have conducted the most recent and relevant research.
Recognizing previous work is essential.


== Research Questions (1--3 questions)

In this chapter, elaborate on the research question(s) introduced in the introduction.
Strive for specificity, and consider including sub-questions.
Explain the relevance of each question.
Pay careful attention to the terms used in your questions, particularly those that describe the aspects you intend to analyze.
When central concepts in your research questions lack precise definitions in existing literature (which is common), provide concise definitions.


== Methodology (1/2 pages)

Describe the data you plan to use and justify why it is appropriate for addressing your research questions.
Address potential challenges in obtaining data and ethical considerations, such as privacy, based on your research field.

Provide a rough explanation of your methods for collecting, generating, and acquiring relevant data.
Explain how you will analyze the data, including quantitative or qualitative approaches, relevant metrics, and statistical measures.
This is what will eventually become your thesis' Methodology chapter.


== Expected Results (1/4 page)

Describe the anticipated results or outcomes for each research question, such as a software prototype, a taxonomy, a meta-analysis of previous works, a set of guidelines, or best practices relevant to your research.


== Timetable

Create a timetable for your thesis project to monitor progress and detect any deviations early on.
Include a short description, planned dates, and actual dates for each milestone (see \cref{tab:timetable}).

